I live in Pacific Beach. I have gone to Fish Shop on Garnet (a highly rated seafood restaurant) since they opened and was a regular at Point Loma seafood prior.
I started here with the fish and shrimp ceviche and was NOT disappointed...sorry, it was so friggin good, I ate half before thinking to take a pic...but honestly, it tasted much better than it looked.
I don't know what I had actually because I asked the lady at the register (literally, probably the sweetest person i've ever ordered food from) to choose for me, since she knows what's freshest and BEST! (although she said everything is fresh)
My daughter had a carne asada burrito...(i JUST asked her how she liked it and from her bedroom she said "I LOVED IT!")
I came with 5 friends that were all very happy with their food as well.
I highly recommend you check out Costa Azul Mariscos...I'll be back next time i'm down Southüëç<//Review>

<Review>BY far one of BEST attractions in DTLA! The HIGHLIGHT of the weekend and the BEST way to end  and start a new week! You Cannot lose going here! The market is EXTREMELY well-managed by Adam and Robert! Super clean and secure,security guards all over! There's a hand washing station and hand sanitizer in almost every corner. There is a limit to how many people can be on the premises, which is closely monitored by SUPER FRIENDLY staff. EVERYONE IS HAPPY THERE! You can use your EBT card there, as a matter of fact it is ENCOURAGED, and they even MATCH your money dollar for dollar! Robert wants EVERYONE to enjoy the experience so he came up with the program! Gotta LOVE THE GUY!!
Oh HAPPY DAYS ARE SUNDAYS AT THE DTLA FARMER'S MARKET! You can find FRUITS, VEGETABLES, BREADS, CHEESES, KOREAN BBQ AND KIMCHE, YOGURT, AMAZING POPCORN,FRESH JUICES, PLANTS (The LA Garden) , CBD PRODUCTS, ALL ESSENTIAL PRODUCTS FOR YOUR HOME AND BODY (Francesco Palmiri),and just SO MUCH MORE!
I have been going to this market for 6 years and I ABSOLUTELY LOVE IT AND THE PEOPLE WHO SELL AND RUN IT! HIGHLY HIGHLY RECOMMEND!</Review><user>106446641095894521188</user>< user_name>

< text>
Great farmers market! get my lettuce, carrots, onions, leaks, cilantro, tomatoes, etc etc etc.
Plus the booth that sells homemade pita bread and five different flavors of hummus  is awesome, another booth has the best home-made tamales, beef, chicken, pork, chile and cheese, Muy Rico! They remind me of my moms. Great plants, soap, & incense. Home made baked goods. There's something for everyone at the Historic Downtown Farmers Market. Sundays 9am-3pm.<//text>

110342893114132230408<//user>
<Name>Karen Graves</Name><Time>1601088756195< /Time>< Rate>
5< /Rate>
<Review>I love going to the market on Sundays. Upon arrival, there is a person stationed at the entrance to help control traffic flow. That person informs you about wearing a face mask, keeping your distance, and exiting at the other end.  Often, I find I have to wait about 2 minutes before I can enter because only a certain number of people can be in the open space market at one time. The person at the other end communicates how many people exited the market which determines how many people can enter. I am happy the same vendors return each week and are set up in the same spot generally making my shopping experience easier. I like being spoken to by the vendors as I move among the crowd. I am becoming a regular. I purchase yogurt, berries, and green leaf items. I create my own fruit smoothies with the items. Everything is fresh because I've noticed these items cannot stay in my refrigerator for a week. I have to use the items and purchase again the next week. My goal is to improve my health through exercise and better eating habits. Items I need to try are the honey and a few of the flat breads. I noticed a vendor or two offered aroma therapy. So I have to try those as well.</Review><Pics>None<//Pics>< resp>
None< /resp>

<Rating>5</Rating>< text>
Found my go to Plumber(s).

Giovanni showed up in the time window.  He initially came to fix the kitchen drain which part of the pipes had started to disintegrate.  He gave me the options to fix only the parts that were damaged or the redo the entire time.  I opted to do the entire drain since this is a rental and all the piping is very old and I'd rather just get it all done now. started with the Asi Sabe Mexico, translated to ‚ÄòThat‚Äôs Mexico‚Äô on the check, a Watermelon and Cucumber Cocktail made with Blanco Taquilla, Lime, and a Tajin rim served in a short glass. It was light and refreshing on the first sip but very cucumber heavy and continued to linger well after. It was too much cucumber and I did not finish the drink. I returned 3/4ths of the drink when I ordered something else. It was $11 and was included on the bill. *(I know businesses are struggling with staffing and financing so I did not say anything- I was happy to know it added to the bill and tip the server received)*

I switched to a Paloma. It was served in a pint glass with a salt rim. $10. Delicious!

We started with a small Guacamole for $9.99. It was made with nice chunks of avocado. It lacked a bit of lime but was very fresh. It was served with a side of Salsa and fresh Tortilla Chips. The Salsa was very good and if you only want the Chips and Salsa they are $3.75. We got a refill of chips and we‚Äôre not charged for them.

For dinner I had Chile Relleno en Crema de Epazote y Camar√≥n. $18.25. A poblano pepper stuffed with crab and shrimp. I substituted the white rice for the Cilantro Rice and I think that was my mistake. The Cilantro Rice was very good but more wet like a Risotto. The dish was topped with a very tasty cream sauce but might have been over powered or lost within the rice.

One of my companions ordered the Carne de Puerco en Salsa Verde. $18.25. They said the Pork was cooked perfectly and the Salsa Verde had a strong lime flavor. They also substituted the white rice for the Cilantro rice. We both agreed the dish might have been better as designed on the menu with the white rice. They also had the Asi Sabe Mexico and agreed it had a heavy cucumber flavor. They did however finished their drink.

The last of our party ordered the Tacos Poblanos de Arrachera. $16.95. Steak Tacos in blue corn tortillas, with sliced and grilled poblano peppers.  They said they were good but wished the flank steak had been salted further. They ordered a Passion Fruit Frozen Margarita with a salt rim and said it was delicious! (Price unknown as we split the check)

This restaurant gets a lot of praise and maybe My expectations were set my too high because everything on the menu was a traditional Mexico dish. Overall 7 out of 10.</text>
</record></dataset><record>

< Review>
We showed up here looking for a Mexican restaurant. We were shuttled to the patio which was cold and damp. Then we looked at the "cusine" described in the menu which was $16.00 tacos.

I am so tired of businesses bowing to the state rules. The state is going  to drive you out of business so why not just treat the customers visiting you like friends and give them a great comfortable dining experience.

We walked out and found a Mexican restaurant with food not cuisine.

We didn't stay so I can't legitimately so it was all bad so if you want cuisine next to a heat lamp go for it.</Review>

<date>1541788316063<//date><rating>3< /rating><review>Loved the ambience of Mayahuel, great location right across the street from the capital. Parking garage right next door. I went with a large group and they pulled tables together to accommodate us. Our server was attentive and the food was quick.  The food in my opinion was just okay. It was good but it wasn't fabulous. I ordered the pozole salad which looked small but was very filling and had large chunks of chicken, a bit tangy though. The chips and salsa are to die for! I will likely go back to hang at the bar but I would be okay passing on the food. Everyone at our table did enjoy the meal, no complaints but no compliments either.<//review>< pics>

< Name>
Katharine King<//Name>
<date>1575149004007<//date>< Rating>
3<//Rating>
< Review>
I saw some articles online said this restaurant qualified for Michelin standard.  Turned out was in area, and decided to give a try.
The restaurant decorated so nicely, and people there were so friendly.
Appertizer was perfect, plated nicely and tasted really good, and kind of fun.
Carnitas was really flavored, but maybe b/c it's in Bay area, people tended to be healthy, so they took all pork fat/skin off, so there's some flavor missed there.
I guess they didn't not expect people ordered Pastel de Mango, so the top glazed layer still frozen, but I still liked the cake a lot.
The reason I gave 3 stars b/c alough their service were friendly, but very sloppy.  When Carnitas came, I had to find somebody to bring me the tortillas.  And then I found there was no fork.  Especially at this level restaurants, tap water NOT supposed to be served.
The dishes are really goodÔºå but towards to Michelin star there's a long way to go.<//Review>

<user_name>Imelda RubioLeyva< /user_name><Time>1527216890876<//Time>< Rate>
3</Rate>
< review>
Vegan pistachio mole was bomb!
The plantain mole was too sweet for a savory dish. potato taquitos for my grandson were super yummy and the service was pretty great! But.. I only gave it 3 stars because I expected more elegance and class from this place. It was not suitable for a Christian family celebrating a courthouse wedding. I went from reviews ranting how great this place was and was happy to hear they had good vegan selections. However, the  bar was the main attraction. Two bars to be exact! Reminded me of clubs in Mexico I used to attend as a teenager before I grew up.  For the high prices of those entrees I just cannot say I would go again. Either go all out and keep your bars and basketball game full blast or tone it down and give it a classy touch but it's just not working as is.<//review>

We were a group of four girls I felt like we were discriminated against and the waiters focused on getting us out of there by rushing us out. One of them said to us "are you finished yet?" with such a horrible attitude. The waiters were very consistent with rushing us out every 10-15 minutes but not anyone else around us, some people had been there since we arrived and they were never rushed or did we see waiters going to their table so much. Being Hispanic and getting treated this way in a "mexican restaurant" is the worst feeling.</Text>

<Text>I had come here a little while ago for a business trip and the food was okay. I saw the reviews on Google that this would be the best most authentic Mexican food he would find in all of Sacramento but I was actually very disappointed, the rice did not have a lot of flavor, and the beans tasted like they had a metallic or metal flavor like they were in a can or tin for a long time. I shared it with someone else just to double-check that I was wasn't imagining the flavor but they also had confirmed that it had a metal taste

the waiter was very kind in the beginning but then his personality changed as soon as there was an error in the bill, the manager came and also had a little attitude

if you are Hispanic and looking for authentic Mexican food I don't recommend this location. over priced for what it is, and the food is okay not that great,

< review>
Very impressive assortment of items on the menu, but not so many that it was hard to choose. The Enchiladas de Mole was amazing! I could tell the mole was house made with care and maybe even some love. It was bursting with flavor and perfectly complemented the chicken in the enchiladas.

In addition to the regular menu, they also have a vegan menu that's equally full of variety and creativity.

What a wonderful lunchtime experience. The place looked like it would be fun at night as well. I highly recommend stopping in when you're nearby. It's even worth a trip all by itself!<//review>

</record></dataset><record>
< text>
I've been here twice and the food was delicious both times. 1st time what my friend had wasn't as great as what I got which was the appetizer with the small little crunchy tacos called taquitos de requeson. But we shared the appetizer chorizo y queso Oaxaca en bolillo tostado and those were great. For my entree I had the steak with a chile verde enchilada and Spanish rice. Let me tell you as someone who's grown up with authentic home made Mexican food their chile verde is one of the best I've ever had! If you have anything with that chile verde it'll be amazing.

This 2nd time around we went with a group of friends and I had the chile verde enchiliadas again great. 2 others had the shrimp ceviche which had a lot of shrimp unlike some other restaurants, this was mainly shrimp with little veggies and it tasted fresh and great with tostadas on the side. Another friend had the dobladitas de chile de poblano which wasn't what she had expected since the menu said blue tortillas filled with cheese it had like one of those along with some other small finger foods on the plate, but she liked it. We all shared the chips and salsa and the salsa was tasty. For dessert me and another friend had the Mazapan with ice cream which btw doesn't crumble like the candy and is hella good. I've never had Mazapan made from scratch, they make their own. 2 other friends had the mango cake which comes with 2 slices of cake. I'm not a big mango fan but this cake was good it had the texture of a yellow cake kinda spongy, topped with a tart mango topping, and the filling was a creamy mango filling. Overall this place is delicious and even had mariachis while we were there. It's a great location for things to do afterwards also.< /text>

<text>We were downtown to watch the IMAX movie and found this place. It turns out it is the hottest new Mexican Restaurant in the area and we were not disappointed. <username>Michael Murza< /username><review>We were extremely happy to learn that Mayahuel has a dedicated Vegan menu.  When we arrived, we decided to sit at the bar (it was about a 15 minute wait for 2 at 7pm on a Thursday night).  The bartender was extremely friendly and accommodating, and quickly took our drink order. We soon ordered our appetizer, which was the Sikil P'ak, a delicious pumpkin seed dip. I would highly recommend this as a perfectly sized appetizer to get you ready for your meal.

We then got our main dishes.  I got the Pistachio Spicy Mole and she got the Huitlacoche Enchiladas.  While the enchiladas were well constructed and incredibly tasty, the Pistachio Spicy Mole absolutely blew me away.  It was rich with deep flavors and was perfectly paired with the portobello mushrooms; I could not have enough of this dish.

While I want to get the Pistachio Spicy Mole the next time I go, I feel like I would be depriving myself of some of the other vegan items they are offering.  Everything I tried was delicious, and everything else on the menu looked similarly delicious.

As I said, we went for the vegan menu.  After our experience, we will definitely be returning for the vegan menu, which the bartender noted would be rotating relatively frequently, so there will likely always be something new to try.

Sacramento is beginning to have more vegan options, and I think Mayahuel is offering one of the most complete and elevated vegan menus in the city. I can't wait to go back.< /review>< Date>
1521864721505< /Date>

<UserId.>112641601394969061980<//UserId.><username>Samara Henry<//username>< Time>
1507503941000</Time>
<rate>5</rate>< Review>
I came here with some coworkers for happy hour on a Friday evening. We chose to sit outside since the weather was beautiful. The outdoor seating is what lured us into the restaurant in the first place. The hanging lights, the cozy/chic seating and the music created the perfect ambience. You can not go wrong with the $5 margaritas for happy hour which were absolutely delicious. The guacamole is absolutely amazing and a must. I had the carnitas dinner which was equally delicious and came with pick, guac, beans and my choice of either flour or corn tortillas.  One of my coworkers had the cevice, which was a huge portion, and she finished the whole thing. My other coworker got the tostadas with pulled chicken from the happy hour menu which I also thought was a great portion size. I would highly recommend this spot if you're ever in the area.<//Review>

< Text>
Ok picture yourself in the Capital City of California on a Saturday and you are craving tacos.  Well all the taquerias are closed but this place is open.  They have Modelo Especial and Victoria on Tap.   You have to pay for chips and salsa but the salsa is good.  You order Tacos de Arrachera which come in blue corn tortillas and satisfy your craving.  If you really want to throw it down this is a temple to tequila.....I am sure your liver wont mind.</Text>
